[[Category:English_words_with_multiple_etymologies]]

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-strain.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Etymology 1===
Anglo-Saxon ''[[str&#275;on]]'', ''[[gestr&#275;on]]'', "gain", "property"; ultimately cognate with Latin ''[[strues]]'', "heap".

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

#[[race|Race]]; [[stock]]; generation; [[descent]]; [[family]].
#:''They say this year's flu virus is a particularly virulent '''strain'''.''
#[[hereditary|Hereditary]] [[character]], [[quality]], or [[disposition]].
#[[rank|Rank]]; a [[sort]].

===Etymology 2===
Old French ''[[estreindre]]'' (confer French ''[[étreindre]]''), "to grip", Latin ''[[stringere]]'', "to draw tight together", "to tie".

====Noun====
{{en-noun|-}}

#{{uncountable}} {{engineering}} The amount by which a [[material]] deforms under [[stress]] or [[force]], given as a ratio of the deformation to the initial dimension of the material and typically symbolised by ε is termed the [[engineering]] strain.  The true strain is defined as the natural [[logarithm]] of the ratio of the final dimension to the initial dimension.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

#To [[exert]] or [[struggle]], especially to [[stretch]] too far.
#:''Sitting in back, I '''strained''' to hear the speaker.''
#To [[apply]] a [[force]] or forces to
#To [[tighten]] the [[string]]s of a [[musical]] [[instrument]]; to [[uplift]] one's [[voice]]

